The reason your Docker build takes so much time (and sends over 1GB of data) is because **Docker is sending your entire project folder to the Docker Daemon as the "build context"** before it even starts building the images!

You have a massive amount of local files that Docker doesn't need to build your app:
- **`.venv/`**: ~670MB (Your local Python virtual environment)
- **`frontend/node_modules/`**: ~100MB+ (Your local Node dependencies)
- **`backend/vast_challenge.db`**: 16GB! (The SQLite DB)
- **`backend/VAST-Challenge-2022/`**: 17GB! (The raw CSV dataset)

Because there was no `.dockerignore` file, Docker was trying to bundle all these up and send them to its internal engine every single time you ran `docker-compose up --build`.

### ✅ I just fixed this for you!

I have created a `.dockerignore` file in your project root with the following contents:
```text
.venv/
node_modules/
__pycache__/
.mypy_cache/
.git/
backend/vast_challenge.db
backend/VAST-Challenge-2022/
frontend/dist/
frontend/node_modules/
```

**Now, if you cancel your current build (`Ctrl+C`) and run it again:**
```bash
docker-compose up --build
